      <h2>Noise: The Silent Advantage</h2>
      <p>This is the single biggest differentiator. A gas generator at full load is loud — typically 70–90 dB, which is enough to require hearing protection within minutes. On residential job sites, it's a guaranteed source of neighbour complaints. On commercial sites near occupied spaces, it might violate local noise ordinances.</p>
      <p>A portable power station like the <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0GWHKXZ7D?tag=sciencesolved-20">Oscal 3600SE</a> or <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0FGHLKGPW?tag=sciencesolved-20">Jackery HomePower 3000</a> produces only the gentle hum of a cooling fan — roughly 30–45 dB. That's quieter than a normal conversation. You can have a discussion next to it, take a phone call, or work inside a finished home without disturbing the occupants.</p>
      <p>For contractors doing interior renovations, finish carpentry, or maintenance work in occupied buildings, the noise advantage alone justifies the switch.</p>

      <h2>Emissions and Indoor Use</h2>
      <p>Gas generators produce carbon monoxide (CO) — a colourless, odourless gas that kills dozens of people every year when generators are used indoors or too close to open windows. OSHA requires gas generators to be placed at least 20 feet from building openings, and they must never be used inside.</p>
      <p>Portable power stations produce zero emissions. You can run one inside a finished basement, on a scaffolding platform, inside a trailer, or in a garage without any ventilation concerns. For winter work, indoor renovations, and any job site with limited outdoor space, this is a massive safety and convenience advantage.</p>

      <h2>Power Output: Where Generators Still Win</h2>
      <p>Raw power output is where gas generators still hold an edge — especially at the high end. The <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B08DJ9XF32?tag=sciencesolved-20">Honda EB10000</a> produces 10,000W of continuous power. That will run multiple compressors, a full table saw setup, a welder, and lights simultaneously. No battery-powered station on the market can match that today.</p>
      <p>However, for most contractors, the question isn't "can I power a full workshop?" — it's "can I power my specific tool set?" For a crew of 1–3 people running typical job-site tools (miter saw, circular saw, compressor, lights, chargers), a 3000–3600W power station like the <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0FGHLKGPW?tag=sciencesolved-20">Jackery HomePower 3000</a> or <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0GWHKXZ7D?tag=sciencesolved-20">Oscal 3600SE</a> handles everything.</p>

      <h2>Runtime: Fuel vs Battery</h2>
      <p>A gas generator with a 5-gallon tank can run for 10–18 hours on a full tank, depending on load. Refuelling takes 5 minutes. In theory, it can run indefinitely.</p>
      <p>A portable power station runs until its battery is depleted. A 3600Wh station running a 1500W tool draws about 2.4 hours of runtime at full load. At half load, it's 4–5 hours. For a full working day, you need to either recharge (solar, wall outlet, vehicle) or have multiple stations.</p>
      <p>For continuous heavy use — think all-day sawing, grinding, or welding — gas generators still offer more practical runtime. But for typical job-site use where tools run intermittently and total daily draw is 1000–2000Wh, a single 3000Wh+ station lasts the full day.</p>

      <h2>Total Cost of Ownership</h2>
      <p>Let's run the numbers for a 5-year comparison:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Gas generator (Honda EB10000-class):</strong> ~$2,500 upfront + $60/month gasoline ($3,600) + $200/year maintenance ($1,000) = ~$7,100 over 5 years</li>
        <li><strong>Battery station (3600Wh class):</strong> ~$2,000 upfront + $0 fuel + $0 maintenance = ~$2,000 over 5 years. Add $500 for a solar panel setup and you still come out ahead.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>The battery station saves roughly $5,000 over 5 years — not counting the value of working indoors without noise complaints, or the time saved not refuelling and maintaining a generator.</p>

      <h2>Portability and Job-Site Logistics</h2>
      <p>A gas generator filled with fuel is heavy and awkward. The Honda EB10000 weighs over 200 lbs — you're not carrying it anywhere without a truck or trailer.</p>
      <p>A 3000Wh+ power station like the <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0FGHLKGPW?tag=sciencesolved-20">Jackery HomePower 3000</a> weighs about 70 lbs with an integrated hand truck. You roll it up a ramp, across a job site, and into an elevator without breaking a sweat. Smaller stations like the <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0DG8JQNS4?tag=sciencesolved-20">OUPES Mega 1</a> (under 30 lbs) can be carried in one hand up a ladder.</p>

      <h2>When to Keep the Generator</h2>
      <p>Gas generators still make sense when:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>You consistently need more than 3600W of continuous power (welding, large compressors, multiple heavy tools)</li>
        <li>You work on sites with zero access to grid power for days at a time and no solar charging option</li>
        <li>You already own a generator that's paid for and in good working order</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>When to Switch to Battery</h2>
      <p>Portable power stations are the better choice when:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>You work indoors or near occupied spaces (noise and emissions matter)</li>
        <li>You're a solo contractor or small crew running tools up to 3600W total</li>
        <li>You value low maintenance and want to stop buying gasoline</li>
        <li>You want to reduce your carbon footprint and job-site pollution</li>
        <li>Your local jurisdiction has noise or emissions restrictions on job sites</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>The Bottom Line</h2>
      <p>For most contractors in 2026, a portable power station is the better primary power source. The noise, emissions, and fuel-cost advantages are compelling, and the power output of modern units like the <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0GWHKXZ7D?tag=sciencesolved-20">Oscal 3600SE</a> or <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0FGHLKGPW?tag=sciencesolved-20">Jackery HomePower 3000</a> covers 90% of job-site needs.</p>
      <p>The smartest play might be both: a battery power station for daily use (silent, cheap, clean) and keep an old gas generator in the truck for those rare days when you need truly massive power. But if you're buying new today, start with battery. The gas generator's days on the job site are numbered.</p>

